  <span id="freeText4535643299925754762" style="display:none">This book was an unprecedented journey for me. It is a true story about the destroyed lives of millions of people who were sentenced to 5-10-15-25 years prison or death sentence during the Stalinist era. It is told by Lev Razgon, who has spend a total of 17 years as a prisoner in Soviet GULAG for political reasons. This memoir is not so much about the author's life, as it is about the people he met during his imrpisonment, their lives, as well as his honest account of the Soviet world, filled with everyday fear of being detained, of your relatives being detained, and marked by a completely unconceivable inhumane attitude towards millions of people. <br /><br />For me this book is not about the horrible things that happen in prisons, the reader gets the gist of this too. It is about the impossible and the limitless. Naively thinking that there are some limits to cruelty and injustice proved wrong. These millions of people, who experienced unbelievable, utterly inhumane treatment, are sadly left pretty much forgotten by history. It still strikes me how much is written and how often it is reminded about Hitler times and all the crimes against humanity (as it should be done) and how little is to hear about the crimes against humanity in the Soviet Union. Well, this book is a memory of these crimes. It is about the limitless cruelty that people can reach and the limitless strength of people to survive.<br /><br />This book should be read and reread, it will be a comparable cruelty to leave these memories die. I hope that those who come across this book, will actually read it and will not be discouraged by the hard to digest topic and the very small number of people, who have read it and reviewed it. Again, this book is much much more than an account of prison life, it is about the lives of very interesting people, some of them the elites of the communist party. Every story is a different life, worth telling and there is so much to take from each. <br /><br />I learned two major things from this book. Anything is possible, literally anything. Human rights, the rule of law, justice as we know it in developed democracies is a bliss and should not be taken for granted. And the second thing that i will take from this book is that people are very strong, flexible and adaptable creatures. People can survive the impossible and achieve the impossible. The struggles and problems that we, the privileged people from developed democracies face are a joke, and we have no whatsoever excuse to not fight for our dreams. In this sense this book is the best motivational biography i have ever read. <br /><br />I must also mention that the author is a very good writer, journalist by profession. He makes all the fear, all the injustice, all the impossible very palpable and unforgettable. Take your time with it. If you rush it can leave you with an experience similar to entering the Hermitage and having only a few hours to spend there. The shock will be unprecedented at the beginning, but naturally wear out because of the rush. As with the Hermitage, this book needs quality time for digestion. And if you think that "Catch-22" by Joseph Heller is a good account of absurdity, you should definitely try this true story.</span>
